<br>
1. There are no corpses when you die. You simply lose some con, xp and return to your bind point.<br>
2. You can avoid all of the death penalty completely (except a miniscule xp hit) by being rezzed.<br>
3. There is no time limit on the rezzes.<br>
4. You can chat with people while waiting, and see what's happening in the area around where you die, so you no longer miss half the battle.<br>
5. Everyone can /bind now, albeit at select locations near cities where bind stones are found.<br>
6. Gear for all levels up to 30th is sold in shops. This is gear you actually WANT to wear.<br>
7. Vendors don't cheat you. Everything sells for half of what you buy it for.<br>
8. Tradeskills can make armor that is phenomenal, and better than purchased armor.<br>
9. Tradeskills also make armor that is usable at any level, even past 30th.<br>
10. Camping for spawns has been reduced to a short wait (up to a day game time) in the WORST case scenario, in most cases it's a few short minutes.<br>
11. When doing quests, everyone in the group gets the quest reward at the same time.<br>
12. Sitting and camping single camps does not give you as much experience as clearing multiple camps.<br>
13. The longer a monster has been around, the more experience it gives for a kill.<br>
14. Pulling and killing multiple monsters at a time rewards huge experience bonuses, sometimes as great as the base xp for the creatures.<br>
15. Due to the last rule, it is beneficial to group as you will gain far MORE experience in a group played well than soloing.<br>
16. Every class can viably solo all the way to 50 from the start. Some have it harder than others, but none have it as hard as any in EQ.<br>
17. Every class has a LARGE number of abilities that allow them to be fre more versatile than any class in EQ.<br>
18. The large number of class abilities and overlap lends to a better groundwork for designing real strategy and tactics to combat foes than EQ.<br>
19. The classes are at LEAST as balanced as EQ, and the vast majority of players agree they are balanced far better.<br>
20. The CON rating in DAoC is ALWAYS accurate as to if you can fight a mob. If it's blue, it's soloable.<br>
21. Trivial mobs (greys) (greens in EQ) will not interfere with you (attack you) since they know they will lose.<br>
22. Mobs respawn at a rate between 30 seconds and five minutes, so there is no downtime waiting for things to kill.<br>
23. You can regen from zero health, stamina and mana in DAoC in less than a minute at any level of the game. EQ takes forever just to Med.<br>
24. Buffs are permanent until the death of the buffer or the buffee, no need to refresh them.<br>
25. Epic quests are availiable for all classes, run from 15th to 50th level, and are very eventful and detailed, far more so than EQ.<br>
26. Quests in DAoC revolve around doing a large number of things to complete the quests, whereas in EQ they usually revolve around camping a few rare spawns and wasting hours in boredom. At least in DAoC you are always doing something instead of camping.<br>
27. Player tradeskills produce items superior to what you can buy at vendors.<br>
28. You can finance yourself very, very well using tradeskills by doing consignments.<br>
29. If you make an item to improve skill, you can reclaim most of the cost of the item by destroying it with the /salvage command.<br>
30. Weapons and armor share superiority over and weaknesses against other types of weapons and armor. Mobs are the same way.<br>
31. There is no need for food or drink.<br>
32. Everyone always has a lightsource, you don't need items for it.<br>
33. There is a builtin, onscreen compass, so you always know what direction you are facing.<br>
34. If you become stuck in an object (as can happen in EQ, albeit rarely) the /stuck command will log you out and back in at a safe point.<br>
35. There is NO MOB PATHING in DAoC. The AI knows where it can and can't be, and does not have to follow a poorly defined path like mobs in EQ do (2nd floor of Hate for example).<br>
36. Items will be given back to you if you hand things in wrong (or to the wrong person) for a quest.<br>
37. Money is weightless in DAoC.<br>
38. You can make change anywhere in DAoC, no need to visit the vault.<br>
39. All weapons, armor, items, and mobs have a rating equivalent to the /consider command in EQ. This locks all of the above into a set level range.<br>
40. Using items outside your level range is impractical, and will destroy the items. This prevents twinking and powerlevelling.<br>
41. You do not have to be in a group to get experience from a kill you assist with. You get xp accodring to the amount of help you give out. This prevents kill stealing.<br>
42. You will NOT lose the components you use to make an item if your tradeskill combine attempt fails.<br>
43. No clicking to drag things around with a tradeskill, the necessary items are automatically taken out of your inventory on success.<br>
44. More tha one person can use a given forge, loom, smithy etc at a time. No more waiting in line.<br>
45. While there are issues with lag and linkdeath, by and large they are FAR less frequent than everquest's problems.<br>
46. There are NO ZONES, in the EQ sense, in this game. The only time you &quot;zone&quot; is when entering a city or dungeon. The rest of the gameworld is perfectly seamless.<br>
47. There are horses in DAoC, anyone can use them, they are fun to ride, and therefore you don't need to beg the services of a porting class to get somewhere.<br>
48. Any attempts to heal or buff lower level players will deny them xp. This prevents powerlevelling.<br>
49. There are no hacks (ala SHowEQ) as of yet that allow players to take unfair advantage of others in the game.<br>
50. All gear can be customised by changing the colors with dyes, giving a single piece of gear dozens of possible looks.<br>
51. All gear can also be customized with patterns, giving a single piece of gear hundreds of possible looks when combined with the different colors.<br>
52. All gear has graphics that are unique to its type, and often, unique to the item itself. EQ has countless problems with items that have no graphics with them, or share the same graphics with other items.<br>
53. You cannot lose a level due to death, you can only bottom out at 0xp in your current level. This means once you make 50 it's yours forever, the level grind comes to a permanent end.<br>
54. The chat system in DAoC, while a bit buggy at the moment, has far more capability that EQ's chat system, even considering the promised changes with SoL.<br>
55. Guilds have nine levels of member rankings now, from trial member to full guildmaster.<br>
56. You can define what capability you wish to give to your guild officers on a power by power basis.<br>
57. Guild alliances are a &quot;guild of guilds&quot; with thier own separate chat channels. Everyone in all guilds in the alliance can see the alliance chat channel.<br>
58. Due to the skill system in DAoC, characters of the same race and class can be radically different from eachother with regards to the magic they use and the skills they possess. This is a diversity that EQ isn't capable of.<br>
59. DAoC has far more races and character classes than EQ does, and all classes have unique abilities that no other class has, even if they do share some abilities among all classes.<br>
60. Groups may go as high as 8 players, whereas EQ can only handle 6.<br>
61. The grouping system provides a publishing and search feature that allows you to quickly and easily find classes and levels you need for your group, or to publish your own talents so those looking can find you. This is ten times the grouping system that everquest has.<br>
62. DAoC has a unique RvR combat system that pits the three realms on a given server against eachother. Their system on PvP could easily have a top 100 list created on why it's the best PvP system out there. As it is, this means that DAoC will have a unique form of gameplay that cannot be found on any other MMORPG on the market today.<br>
63. DAoC has quests, and &quot;uber&quot; monsters, giving it all of the endgame features of games like everquest in ADDITION to the RvR system.<br>
64. One does not have to participate in RvR, although by its design it's appealing even to those who do not like PvP environments.<br>
65. Guild chat has a private, officer-only channel. Only a player who has been a guild officer can truly understand what a huge boon this is.<br>
66. Your friends list can hold more people than EQ's, and in addition you will be notified with a message the instant a friend of yours logs into or out of the game.<br>
67. DAoC high level gear LOOKS like high level gear. You won't be stuck with newbie graphics that make you look like a beggar at 50. You could MAKE yourself look like a beggar if you really wanted to.<br>
68. DAoC has an item decay system that is well thought out and will give it a much more stable economy than everquest.<br>
69. Combat in DAoC is vastly superior to any existing MMORPG. Each class gains new styles and moves that stack with previous versions, and build off them so that you can make chain attacks. Combat is not just clicking a button anymore like in EQ.<br>
70. The graphics in DAoC are so superior to EQ that they easily deserve their own top 100 reasons list. ANyone who has seen the sunsets, varying levels of mists, fog and rain, and any part of the countryside will understand.<br>
71. You can add the emblem of your guild to your gear. Place it on your cloaks and shields to make your guild more well known.<br>
72. Mythic provides phenomenal customer support. Verant should hang thier heads in shame, it's like comparing grains of dust to diamonds.<br>
73. Mythic, as a company, is at the whim of the playerbase. Any changes that players express a desire for will make it into the game.<br>
74. Mythic is not afraid to answer posts directly, and to apologise for their mistakes. VI is famous for their holier than thou attitude and refusal to admit they have done anything wrong.<br>
75. Mythic always sides with the customer on any issue by default, they give the benefit of the doubt.<br>
76. Patches in DAoC take a matter of minutes. Mythic has yet to release a patch that did not add at least three new and excellent features to the game.<br>
77. The roleplaying servers in DAoC are actually real roleplaying servers. RP is enforced there, and violators will be banned from RP, with their characters moved to a standard server.<br>
78. DAoC's interface supports scripting and macros, so there is no end to what you can code into their game on your end. Expect to see player-created packages that add content in the near future.<br>
79. DAoC has phenomenal sound effects. While hunting in the avalon marshes, this player stopped to listen for a while. Between the peepers, crickets, buzzing insects, occasional bullfrog, splash of a fish on the water, and wolf howl, it is totally indestinguishable from a real marsh. The sounds create the most immersive environment imaginable.<br>
80. The emotes in DAoC (/wave, /bow and /dance for example) have far better and more lifelike effects than everquest is capable of producing with their modeling system.<br>
81. DAoC has a far, far higher content to space ratio than everquest. EQ is replete with vast stretches of open, underused space. (Karanas, certain dungeons, etc)<br>
82. DAoC has set the standard for stability and starting content with this launch, and Mythic was disappointed because they had to &quot;rush it&quot; and leave things out. If thier second best attempt is this good, imagine what this game will look like in a year's time.<br>
83. DAoC provides far, far more customiseability to thier user interface than EQ does. You can clone EQ's interface down to the smallest detail, or completely create your own. Having real control over the camera is excellent.<br>
84. Public channels are only availiable in cities. This greatly reduces the amount of off topic garbage one is exposed to in DAoC. It also has the added effect of concentrating player-related economic business in the city zones.<br>
85. Mythic provides prompt service in game when they are made aware of both bugs and issues with unruly players.<br>
86. Mythic is not afraid to take harsh disciplinary action against players that violate their gaming policy. This has the effect of chilling bad behavior and promoting a community roleplaying environment.<br>
87. Mythic provides PUBLIC forums for discussion of their issues with their own staff. Vi once did this, but couldn't handle the criticism and shut their boards down, turning them into a moderated forum that is useless for communicating with their developers.<br>
88. All GMs and customer service agents in DAoC are paid employees of Mythic, rather than players voulnteering their time.<br>
89. The /advice system allows you to both get answers and give advice to those new to the game without bothering CS with trivial issues.<br>
90. Due to the game's inherent design, &quot;lootwhores&quot; simply do not exist. Just think for one second about the problems and anxiety that this simple change puts an end to. No greed in camps, no arguments among guildmates about who gtes their epic next... it's a great paradigm shift.<br>
91. There are no LORE or NODROP items in DAoC. You may do with your gear as you please, be it selling it or giving it away.<br>
92. The /quest feature lists all the quests you have ever completed. The quest journal nicely lists all the quests you are currently running, as well as what the next step is. It's an ingenious system for keeping track of what you are doing.<br>
93. DAoC allows you to earn rank, title, and, promised in the future, the ability to own land and buildings, and even horses.<br>
94. DAoC's quests have some amount of dynamic ability, meaning that though the reward is the same, two different people may experience different paths to complete the quests.<br>
95. DAoC has fewer bugs and more features at release than EQ will have after SoL is released. The only area that EQ beats DAoC in is pure content, and that will change.<br>
96. DAoC doesn't seem to have the same account hacking and hijacking problems that EQ does. Mythic restores lost characters, they don't tell you touch luck, no reimbursements.<br>
97. Mythic's upcoming feature list looks like something out of a RPG player's wet dream. EQ has more of the same in line in SoL, including poorer implementations of some of DAoC's current features.<br>
98. DAoC gives you the numbers right up front for all skills, spells, abilities, and the experience you are awarded up front.<br>
99. The spell effects in DAoC are absolutely gorgeous.<br>
100. Mythic hired TWEETY to be their main PR. /drool... the best VI can do is Absor (sorry bud, Tweety owns you). <p>Raviel Darkfyre<BR>
55th Master of the Whistling Fist<BR>
<b>Insidious Blood</b>
